</caption>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,150,969]" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">Elytra about 1.25 times as long as pronotum. Scutellum large, triangular. Elytra and scutellum densely and finely punctate and pubescent, punctures separated by one to two times their diameter, punctures much finer than those on head and pronotum. Scutellum with arcuate basal lines.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,150,969]" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">Abdomen wide, very gradually narrowing towards apex, densely and finely hairs and punctate, bearing strong long setae in the two sides margin of abdomen, bearing two rows of strong setae in the lateral margin of tergites. Tergites III–V with two basal lines, elevated area between basal lines with rather irregular transverse row of fine punctures, remaining portion of (all) tergites densely and rather finely punctate, surface between punctures strongly iridescent.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,150,969]" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">
Male: Sternite VIII with moderately wide, inverted trapezoidal, in the apex of Sternite VIII triangular concave and with diaphanous semi-membranous extension (
<figureCitation box="[728,822,474,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1836,1860]" captionTargetBox="[161,1426,786,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-271@9.[151,1437,776,1813]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Eccoptolonthus ernsti (Schillhammer, 2011) A. Habitus; B. aedeagus, dorsal (parameral side) view; C. aedeagus, lateral view; D. sternite IX of male; E. stylus of tergite IX of male; F. sternite VIII of male; G. tergite X of male. Scale bars, A=1 mm; B, C, D, E, F, G=0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640485" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640485/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">Figs. 5F</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[834,868,475,502]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[294,1289,194,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[294,1294,181,1911]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eccoptolonthus ernsti (Schillhammer, 2011) A. aedeagus, dorsal (parameral side) view; B. aedeagus, lateral view; C. sternite IX of male; D. tergite X of male; E. sternite VIII of male; F. stylus of tergite IX of male. Scale bars, A, B= 0.18 mm; C, F= 0.24 mm; D= 0.2 mm; E= 0.36 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640489/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">6E</figureCitation>
). Genital segment with stylus of tergite IX simple, approximatively baculiform (
<figureCitation box="[478,574,510,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1836,1860]" captionTargetBox="[161,1426,786,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-271@9.[151,1437,776,1813]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Eccoptolonthus ernsti (Schillhammer, 2011) A. Habitus; B. aedeagus, dorsal (parameral side) view; C. aedeagus, lateral view; D. sternite IX of male; E. stylus of tergite IX of male; F. sternite VIII of male; G. tergite X of male. Scale bars, A=1 mm; B, C, D, E, F, G=0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640485" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640485/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">Figs. 5E</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[585,618,511,538]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[294,1289,194,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[294,1294,181,1911]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eccoptolonthus ernsti (Schillhammer, 2011) A. aedeagus, dorsal (parameral side) view; B. aedeagus, lateral view; C. sternite IX of male; D. tergite X of male; E. sternite VIII of male; F. stylus of tergite IX of male. Scale bars, A, B= 0.18 mm; C, F= 0.24 mm; D= 0.2 mm; E= 0.36 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640489/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">6F</figureCitation>
). Tergite X triangular with moderately emargination (
<figureCitation box="[1212,1311,510,537]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1836,1860]" captionTargetBox="[161,1426,786,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-271@9.[151,1437,776,1813]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Eccoptolonthus ernsti (Schillhammer, 2011) A. Habitus; B. aedeagus, dorsal (parameral side) view; C. aedeagus, lateral view; D. sternite IX of male; E. stylus of tergite IX of male; F. sternite VIII of male; G. tergite X of male. Scale bars, A=1 mm; B, C, D, E, F, G=0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640485" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640485/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">Figs. 5G</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1322,1360,511,538]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[294,1289,194,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[294,1294,181,1911]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eccoptolonthus ernsti (Schillhammer, 2011) A. aedeagus, dorsal (parameral side) view; B. aedeagus, lateral view; C. sternite IX of male; D. tergite X of male; E. sternite VIII of male; F. stylus of tergite IX of male. Scale bars, A, B= 0.18 mm; C, F= 0.24 mm; D= 0.2 mm; E= 0.36 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640489/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">6D</figureCitation>
). Male sternite IX with deeply notched apex, tips of lobes bearing one large black seta (
<figureCitation box="[1049,1149,546,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1836,1860]" captionTargetBox="[161,1426,786,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-271@9.[151,1437,776,1813]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Eccoptolonthus ernsti (Schillhammer, 2011) A. Habitus; B. aedeagus, dorsal (parameral side) view; C. aedeagus, lateral view; D. sternite IX of male; E. stylus of tergite IX of male; F. sternite VIII of male; G. tergite X of male. Scale bars, A=1 mm; B, C, D, E, F, G=0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640485" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640485/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">Figs. 5D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1161,1197,547,574]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[294,1289,194,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[294,1294,181,1911]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eccoptolonthus ernsti (Schillhammer, 2011) A. aedeagus, dorsal (parameral side) view; B. aedeagus, lateral view; C. sternite IX of male; D. tergite X of male; E. sternite VIII of male; F. stylus of tergite IX of male. Scale bars, A, B= 0.18 mm; C, F= 0.24 mm; D= 0.2 mm; E= 0.36 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640489/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">6C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,150,969]" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">
Aedeagus as (
<figureCitation box="[354,484,582,609]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1836,1860]" captionTargetBox="[161,1426,786,1804]" captionTargetId="figure-271@9.[151,1437,776,1813]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 5. Eccoptolonthus ernsti (Schillhammer, 2011) A. Habitus; B. aedeagus, dorsal (parameral side) view; C. aedeagus, lateral view; D. sternite IX of male; E. stylus of tergite IX of male; F. sternite VIII of male; G. tergite X of male. Scale bars, A=1 mm; B, C, D, E, F, G=0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640485" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640485/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">Figs. 5B–C</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[494,566,583,610]" captionStart="FIGURE 6" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1935,1959]" captionTargetBox="[294,1289,194,1902]" captionTargetId="figure-25@10.[294,1294,181,1911]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 6. Eccoptolonthus ernsti (Schillhammer, 2011) A. aedeagus, dorsal (parameral side) view; B. aedeagus, lateral view; C. sternite IX of male; D. tergite X of male; E. sternite VIII of male; F. stylus of tergite IX of male. Scale bars, A, B= 0.18 mm; C, F= 0.24 mm; D= 0.2 mm; E= 0.36 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4640489" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4640489/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">6A–B</figureCitation>
). Median lobe short, apical proton broadly truncate; in lateral view, apical portion of median lobe straight and slightly concave in the middle (parameral side); paramere trilobed apically, median lobe longer than lateral lobe, bearing two long rows of peg setae in the apex of median lobe and three pairs of major setae; bearing a peg seta in the apex of lateral lobe and dense peg setae along medial margin and a major seta at tip of lobe.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="484" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,150,969]" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,763,789]" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="A. Habitus" baseAuthorityName="Schillhammer" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[322,416,763,788]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Eccoptolonthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ernsti">
<emphasis box="[322,416,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">E. ernsti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Li &amp; Zhou" baseAuthorityYear="2011" box="[645,790,763,788]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Pseudohesperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tripartitus">
<emphasis box="[645,790,763,788]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="484">E. tripartitus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The former can be easily distinguished from the latter by following characters: the black antennae; last segment of the maxillary palpi yellowish-brown; pronotum without distinct microsculpture of oblique lines; abdominal tergite III with two basal carinae; sternite IX with apex deeply emarginate; median lobe of aedeagus appearing parallel-sided in ventral view (parameral side); median lobe of aedeagus not distinctly produced ventrally in lateral view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
